# =============================================================================
# Trivy Ignore File — Suppress known acceptable findings
# =============================================================================
# Trivy is a security scanner that checks Terraform files for misconfigurations.
# Some findings are expected for a college project with cost constraints.
# Add check IDs here to suppress them (one per line).
#
# FORMAT:   AVD-AWS-XXXX
# DOCS:     https://avd.aquasec.com/misconfig/
# =============================================================================

# We intentionally use single-AZ RDS (no Multi-AZ) to save ~50% cost.
# In production you'd want Multi-AZ for automatic failover.
AVD-AWS-0080

# ElastiCache transit encryption is disabled intentionally.
# All traffic stays within the private VPC, so TLS adds overhead without benefit.
AVD-AWS-0051

# RDS deletion protection is disabled so terraform destroy works.
# In real production, you'd enable this.
AVD-AWS-0177

# EKS public endpoint access is enabled (so we can run kubectl from our laptops).
# In production, you'd restrict this to specific IP ranges.
AVD-AWS-0041

# RDS not using IAM auth — we use username/password (simpler for college project).
AVD-AWS-0176

# EKS public endpoint access is enabled (so we can run kubectl from our laptops).
# In production, you'd restrict to specific IP ranges or use a VPN.
AVD-AWS-0040

# Unrestricted egress (0.0.0.0/0) on security groups for EKS, RDS, and ElastiCache.
# Nodes need outbound access to pull container images (ECR/Docker Hub), reach AWS APIs,
# and communicate with managed services. Restricting egress would break the cluster.
AVD-AWS-0104

# Public subnets auto-assign public IPs — this is by design.
# Public subnets host the ALB (internet-facing load balancer), which needs a public IP.
AVD-AWS-0164

# S3 state bucket uses SSE-S3 (AES256) encryption, not a customer-managed KMS key.
# CMKs add cost (~$1/month + API charges) with no benefit for a state bucket.
AVD-AWS-0132
